---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'why-cambodia', text: 'Why Retirees Choose Cambodia', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-options', text: 'Visa Options', level: 2 },
  { id: 'insurance-requirements', text: 'Insurance Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-providers', text: 'Recommended Providers', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-access', text: 'Healthcare Access', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Cost Planning', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Thailand for Retirees', href: '/insurance-for/retirees/in/thailand' },
  { title: 'Vietnam for Retirees', href: '/insurance-for/retirees/in/vietnam' },
  { title: 'Senior Insurance', href: '/best/senior-insurance' },
  { title: 'Budget Expat Insurance', href: '/best/budget-expat-insurance' },
  { title: 'Philippines for Retirees', href: '/insurance-for/retirees/in/philippines' },
];

const providerColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'ageLimit', header: 'Max Entry Age' },
  { key: 'preExisting', header: 'Pre-Existing' },
  { key: 'cambodiaNetwork', header: 'Cambodia Network' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly (Age 60)' },
];

const providerRows = [
  { provider: 'Pacific Cross', ageLimit: '70', preExisting: 'Case-by-case', cambodiaNetwork: 'Good (regional)', monthly: '$180-300' },
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', ageLimit: '74', preExisting: 'Covered (24mo wait)', cambodiaNetwork: 'Limited', monthly: '$280-420' },
  { provider: 'Luma Health', ageLimit: '65', preExisting: 'Case-by-case', cambodiaNetwork: 'Good (local specialist)', monthly: '$150-280' },
  { provider: 'IMG Global', ageLimit: '74', preExisting: 'Case-by-case', cambodiaNetwork: 'Limited', monthly: '$220-360' },
];

const costColumns = [
  { key: 'item', header: 'Expense' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly' },
  { key: 'notes', header: 'Notes' },
];

const costRows = [
  { item: 'International Insurance (55-59)', monthly: '$150-260', notes: 'With evacuation coverage' },
  { item: 'International Insurance (60-64)', monthly: '$200-340', notes: 'With evacuation coverage' },
  { item: 'International Insurance (65-69)', monthly: '$280-450', notes: 'With evacuation coverage' },
  { item: 'Local Cambodian Insurance', monthly: '$30-60', notes: 'Very limited coverage' },
  { item: 'Direct medical costs', monthly: '$20-50', notes: 'Out-of-pocket routine care' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Retirees in Cambodia | Visa Guide 2026"
  description="Complete guide to health insurance for retirees in Cambodia. Easy visa, ultra-low costs, Bangkok evacuation, and insurance options for Western retirees in Phnom Penh and Siem Reap."
  headline="Health Insurance for Retirees in Cambodia"
  subheadline="Cambodia offers the easiest visa in Southeast Asia and rock-bottom costs. Healthcare is limited—Bangkok evacuation is standard for anything serious. Here's the practical guide for budget-conscious retirees."
  heroImage="/images/countries/default-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Retiree Quotes"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <p class="text-sm text-neutral-500 mb-4">
    <strong>Affiliate disclosure:</strong> We may earn a commission when you click our links and purchase insurance. This doesn't affect our recommendations or the price you pay.
  </p>

  <h2 id="overview" class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Overview</h2>

  <p class="mb-4">
    Cambodia is Southeast Asia's most accessible retirement destination. The visa situation is simple—renewable long-term stays with minimal requirements. Costs are among the lowest anywhere. Phnom Penh and Siem Reap have established expat communities with surprising amenities.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-4">
    The trade-off: healthcare is limited. Phnom Penh has improving facilities, but for serious conditions, Bangkok (1-hour flight) is the evacuation destination. International insurance with robust evacuation coverage isn't optional—it's essential. This guide covers the realities.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-8">
    <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-3">Key Facts for Retirees</h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Visa:</strong> ER visa (retirement) renewable indefinitely</li>
      <li><strong>Insurance required:</strong> Not for visa, but essential for healthcare</li>
      <li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Basic locally; Bangkok evacuation for serious cases</li>
      <li><strong>Cost of living:</strong> 70-80% lower than US/UK</li>
      <li><strong>Currency:</strong> USD widely used (riel for small transactions)</li>
      <li><strong>Medical evacuation:</strong> Bangkok (1 hour) for serious conditions</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="why-cambodia" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Why Retirees Choose Cambodia</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Ultra-Low Cost of Living</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Cambodia may be the cheapest comfortable retirement destination in the world. $1,000-1,500/month covers a good apartment, food, entertainment, domestic help, and healthcare. Phnom Penh is pricier; Siem Reap and coastal areas even cheaper. Your pension goes further here than almost anywhere.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Easiest Visa in Asia</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    No income proof. No bank accounts. No health checks. The ER (retirement) visa is available to anyone over 55 and costs roughly $300/year including extensions. Renewable indefinitely. No other Asian country makes long-term stays this simple. This alone draws many retirees.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">USD Economy</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Cambodia uses US dollars for most transactions. ATMs dispense dollars. Prices are quoted in dollars. No currency exchange hassle or devaluation risk. This simplifies financial planning significantly compared to other Southeast Asian destinations.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Growing Expat Communities</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Phnom Penh's expat scene includes restaurants, bars, social clubs, and English-speaking services. Siem Reap (near Angkor Wat) has tourism infrastructure and a smaller but active expat community. Sihanoukville has changed dramatically (Chinese development) but still has some expat presence.
  </p>

  <h2 id="visa-options" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Visa Options</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">ER Visa (Retirement)</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    The ER (Extended Stay - Retired) visa is for those 55 and older. Arrive on a standard tourist visa (e-visa works), then convert to ER category through a visa agent. Initial extension is 6 or 12 months. Annual renewals are routine. No income requirements, no health insurance mandates, no residency rules.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">EG Visa (General Business)</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    For those under 55, the EG visa provides similar long-term stays. Technically a business visa but widely used by retirees and digital nomads. Same process: arrive on tourist visa, convert through agent. No actual business activity required.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">The Agent System</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Visa agents handle all extensions and renewals for $250-350/year including fees. They collect your passport, process paperwork, and return it extended. This is how virtually everyone manages long-term stays. It's gray-area but standard practice, tolerated by authorities.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">No Insurance Requirement</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Unlike Thailand or Vietnam, Cambodia doesn't require health insurance for visas. This makes entry easy but means you must arrange coverage independently. Given local healthcare limitations, this is critically important.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Need Cambodia Insurance?"
    description="Bangkok evacuation coverage is essential. Get quotes with proper evacuation benefits."
    buttonText="Get Cambodia Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="insurance-requirements" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Insurance Requirements</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Not Required but Essential</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Cambodia doesn't require health insurance for visas or residency. However, given the healthcare situation, international insurance is practically mandatory. Local hospitals can't handle serious conditions. Without insurance covering Bangkok evacuation and treatment, you're exposed to significant risk.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Bangkok Evacuation Is Key</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    This is the critical coverage component. Bangkok is 1 hour by air with world-class hospitals (Bumrungrad, Bangkok Hospital). Medical evacuation there costs $10,000-20,000 out of pocket. Complex treatment runs $50,000-200,000+. Ensure your policy covers $100,000+ evacuation without restrictive definitions.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">What to Look For</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Prioritize: medical evacuation (to Bangkok or home), inpatient coverage, Thailand network access (you may choose to go to Bangkok for non-emergency care), and pre-existing condition coverage. Outpatient care in Cambodia is cheap enough to self-fund.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Regional vs Global Insurers</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Regional insurers like Pacific Cross and Luma Health understand Southeast Asian healthcare realities. They have Bangkok hospital relationships and coordinate evacuations smoothly. Global insurers (Cigna, Allianz) work too but may have less regional expertise.
  </p>

  <h2 id="recommended-providers" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Recommended Providers</h2>

  <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Pacific Cross — Best for Cambodia</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Regional specialist headquartered in Bangkok. Excellent Thailand hospital network for evacuation care. Understands Cambodia realities. Lower premiums than global insurers. Coordinates evacuations to Bangkok smoothly. Strong choice for retirees staying in Southeast Asia.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Luma Health — Local Expertise</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Cambodia-focused insurer with local office in Phnom Penh. Understands local healthcare landscape. Good relationships with Cambodian and Thai hospitals. Lower premiums. Worth considering for primary Cambodia-based retirement with Bangkok backup.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Cigna Global — Best Global Coverage</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Worldwide coverage with robust evacuation benefits. Guaranteed acceptance option for pre-existing conditions. Higher premiums but comprehensive. Good for retirees who travel frequently or may relocate.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Local Cambodian Insurance</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Forte, Infinity, and other local insurers offer cheap coverage ($30-60/month) but very limited benefits and claims processes can be difficult. Not recommended as primary coverage for Western retirees—useful only as supplement if at all.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Cambodia Insurance Options"
    description="See actual costs for your age and situation. Evacuation coverage included."
    buttonText="Get Personalized Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="healthcare-access" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Healthcare Access in Cambodia</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Phnom Penh Hospitals</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Royal Phnom Penh Hospital, Calmette Hospital, and Sen Sok International have improved significantly. They handle routine care, minor surgeries, and stabilization adequately. English-speaking doctors are available. For anything complex—cardiac, cancer, major trauma—evacuation to Bangkok is standard.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Siem Reap Healthcare</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    More limited than Phnom Penh. Royal Angkor International Hospital handles basics. For anything significant, you'll travel to Phnom Penh or Bangkok. Siem Reap is 1-hour flight or 5-hour drive from Phnom Penh; 1.5-hour flight to Bangkok.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Bangkok as Healthcare Hub</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Many Cambodia retirees use Bangkok for scheduled care—annual checkups, specialist consultations, elective procedures. Bumrungrad and Bangkok Hospital are 1 hour away by air. Some maintain Thai bank accounts and relationships with Thai doctors. The Cambodia-Bangkok healthcare axis is well-established.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Pharmacies</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Pharmacies in Cambodia sell most medications without prescription. Quality varies—stick to chain pharmacies in Phnom Penh. For specialized medications, bring supplies or order from Bangkok. Counterfeit drugs exist; buy from reputable sources.
  </p>

  <h2 id="costs" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Cost Planning</h2>

  <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Total Healthcare Budget</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    For a 60-year-old retiree: international insurance with evacuation ($200-340/month) plus out-of-pocket routine care ($20-50/month) totals roughly $220-390/month. This is lower than most destinations while providing essential evacuation protection.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Cost-Saving Strategies</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>High deductible:</strong> Routine care in Cambodia is extremely cheap—$10 doctor visits, $50 basic procedures. A $5,000 deductible makes sense here. <strong>Asia-only coverage:</strong> Excluding Americas/Europe significantly reduces costs. <strong>Inpatient-only:</strong> Cover hospitalizations and evacuation; self-fund everything else.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">The Total Picture</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    With $1,200-1,800/month total budget (housing, food, entertainment, healthcare), Cambodia offers comfortable retirement. Add $200-350/month insurance, and you're still at $1,400-2,150/month all-in. For those watching costs, it's hard to beat.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 mb-8">
    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Is Cambodia safe for retirees?</h3>
      <p>Phnom Penh and Siem Reap are generally safe for expats. Petty crime exists but violent crime against foreigners is rare. Traffic is chaotic—be careful crossing streets. Infrastructure is developing but inconsistent. Most retirees feel comfortable after adjustment period.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Do I need to speak Khmer?</h3>
      <p>In expat areas of Phnom Penh and Siem Reap, English works for daily life. Khmer is appreciated and helps outside tourist zones. Healthcare facilities catering to expats have English speakers. Many retirees learn basic Khmer over time.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">What if I have a medical emergency?</h3>
      <p>Call your insurance's emergency line immediately. For true emergencies, go to Royal Phnom Penh Hospital or nearest adequate facility for stabilization. Insurance coordinates evacuation to Bangkok once stable. Keep insurance cards and emergency contacts accessible at all times.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">How does the visa agent system work?</h3>
      <p>You find a visa agent (expat forums have recommendations). Give them your passport and fee (~$300/year). They process extension paperwork and return your passport with valid stamps. It takes a few days. This is standard practice—virtually all long-term expats use agents.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Which city is better: Phnom Penh or Siem Reap?</h3>
      <p>Phnom Penh: larger expat community, better healthcare, more amenities, more chaotic. Siem Reap: smaller, quieter, near Angkor Wat, more tourist-oriented, limited healthcare. Many retirees try both before deciding. Some split time between them.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Is Cambodia right for retirees with health conditions?</h3>
      <p>Depends on the condition. Stable, manageable conditions (controlled diabetes, hypertension) work fine with medication management. Complex or unstable conditions requiring specialist care are challenging—Bangkok becomes your primary healthcare destination. Consider whether frequent Bangkok trips are acceptable.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Explore Cambodia?"
    description="Get insurance with proper evacuation coverage before your move."
    buttonText="Get Your Cambodia Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <p class="text-sm text-neutral-500 mt-12">
    This information is for educational purposes. Visa procedures, healthcare quality, and insurance options change. Verify current information with Cambodia-based expat communities. Consider a trial visit before committing to Cambodia retirement. Last updated: May 2026.
  </p>
</PageShell>
